      \field{abstract}{p53 maintains genome integrity either by regulating the transcription of genes involved in cell cycle, apoptosis, and DNA repair or by interacting with partner proteins. Here we provide evidence for a direct physical interaction between the tumor suppressors p53 and BRCA2. We found that the transactivation domain of p53 made specific interactions with the C-terminal oligonucleotide/oligosaccharide-binding-fold domains of BRCA2 (BRCA2CTD). A second distinct site situated on the p53 DNA-binding domain, bound to a region containing BRC repeats of BRCA2 (BRCA2[BRC1-8]) and may contribute synergistically for high affinity association of intact full-length proteins. Overexpression of BRCA2 and BRCA2CTD suppressed the transcriptional activity of p53 with a concomitant reduction in the expression of p53-target genes such as Bax and p21. Consequently, p53-mediated apoptosis was significantly attenuated by BRCA2. The observed physical association of p53 and BRCA2 may have important functional implications in the p53 transactivation-independent suppression of homologous recombination and suggests a possible interregulatory role for both proteins in apoptosis and DNA repair.}
